[1]
Date: Tue, 3 Jun 2002
From: Robert A. LaBudde <ral@lcfltd.com>

Chicken meat injected with water and animal proteins from the Netherlands
--------------------------------------------------
Hydrolyzed proteins are common flavor enhancers used in food
products. The breakdown products of amino acids and nucleotides
improve and strengthen the taste of foods. The most common example
of the use of hydrolyzed proteins is in the culinary use of soy sauce.
Pumping poultry meat or hams or roast beef with a solution of water,
salt, flavorings, and other ingredients is not done entirely for cost
savings. Very lean meat is unpalatable and dry. Addition of moisture
improves juiciness.
Hydrolyzed meat proteins are expensive, typically costing more per
pound than the raw meat ingredient involved.
This so-called "new report" appears to be a slanted story about a
common ingredient. The story was perhaps intended to inflame public
opinion without otherwise informing them. It certainly doesn't appear
to be balanced.
Finally, enzymatic decomposition of DNA and proteins is not likely to
significantly disinfect BSE-contaminated tissues. Prions are
notoriously inert to common proteinases.
--
Robert A. LaBudde, PhD, PAS, Dpl. ACAFS
Least Cost Formulations, Ltd.
Virginia Beach, VA 23464-3239
<ral@lcfltd.com>
