Date: Tue, 03 Jun 2003
From: J Ralph Blanchfield <jralphb@easynet.co.uk> [edited]

Julian Wei-Tze Tang wrote "Perhaps we should alert our Food Standards
Agencies or similar watchdogs to be on renewed lookout for such
"hydrolysed protein-enhanced meat products" entering our countries".
They do not need telling. Panorama misleadingly presented all this as
a new sensational discovery of their own investigation. [The data
were based on a single investigation about which Dr. Blanchfield
raises a question on the validity.] The UK Food Standards Agency
[FSA] (and the interested public) knew all about the "hydrolysed
protein-enhanced meat products" since December 2001, when FSA
published its survey highlighting the mislabelling of chicken
containing added water and hydrolysed proteins; and it was their
subsequent investigation which brought the extent of it to light. The
Dutch authorities have taken action against several companies
identified in the FSA survey.
Those who may not have seen it [are invited to see] the report of 21
May 2003 (i.e. before the Panorama programme) from the FSA Website on
the latest state of play and history of the chicken fraud [see item 3
below].
It is interesting to see the analytical information reported [in the
said FSA press release]. This does not suggest that the undeclared
protein was undetectable.
Knowing about the background, and watching the Panorama programme, I
thought it was a disreputable and sensationalist attempt to claim
credit for bringing the fraud to light while discrediting the Food
Standards Agency -- the message that came through loud and clear was
"The Food Standards Agency is the UK's watchdog -- but it is failing
us"! That is clearly a false message.
--
Prof J Ralph Blanchfield, MBE
Vice President, European Food Law Association of the UK
Adjunct Professor, Michigan State University
<jralphb@easynet.co.uk>
